const PSYCHOLOGY_LAYER = `
CIALDINI'S 7 PRINCIPLES OF INFLUENCE (2021 update, from 6)
  1. Reciprocity   — Give value first. Free tools, guides, insights before ask.
  2. Commitment    — Small yes leads to big yes. Micro-commitments escalate.
  3. Social Proof  — People do what others do. "10,000 teams chose X."
  4. Authority     — Expertise builds trust. Credentials, case studies, data.
  5. Liking        — Similarity + compliments + cooperation + attractiveness.
  6. Scarcity      — Loss aversion > gain seeking. Limited time, seats, stock.
  7. Unity         — Shared identity. "For founders, by founders." Tribal.

JOBS-TO-BE-DONE (Christensen)
Customers "hire" products to do specific jobs. Identify the job this client's
product is hired to do (functional + emotional + social layers). Messaging
addresses the JOB, not the product features. Example: a milkshake isn't hired
for hunger — it's hired to make the morning commute less boring.
  Functional job:  the literal task (clean the kitchen, acquire leads)
  Emotional job:   the feeling sought (pride, relief, confidence)
  Social job:      how the customer wants to be perceived (savvy, caring, in-control)
Write copy that names the job in the customer's words.

BEHAVIORAL ECONOMICS (Kahneman, Thaler)
  Loss aversion:      losses hurt 2.5x more than gains feel good — frame as loss avoidance
  Anchoring:          first number seen influences all subsequent — set high anchor
  Endowment effect:   once "owned," harder to give up — free trials, free tiers, "yours now"
  Social norms:       "10,000 customers chose X" beats "X is great"
  Peak-end rule:      customers remember peak + end — design peak moments + memorable ends
  Choice architecture: default options win 80% of the time — set strategic defaults
  Status quo bias:    inertia is massive — friction to switch, ease to stay

NEUROMARKETING (Dooley, Nielsen)
  Faces in thumbnails → +48% CTR
  Emotional content  → 2.5x more shares than neutral
  Color psychology per CTA: red = urgency, blue = trust, green = go, amber = money
  Font psychology:   serif = tradition, sans = modern, mono = precision/tech
  First impression:  0.05 seconds to form brand judgment — above-the-fold is everything

STORYBRAND (Donald Miller)
Customer is the HERO. Brand is the GUIDE (Yoda, not Luke).
  1. A CHARACTER (customer) — define them
  2. has a PROBLEM (external + internal + philosophical)
  3. and meets a GUIDE (brand — empathy + authority)
  4. who gives them a PLAN (steps or agreements)
  5. and calls them to ACTION (direct + transitional CTA)
  6. that helps them avoid FAILURE (what's at stake)
  7. and ends in SUCCESS (transformation portrait).
This framework outperforms brand-first messaging 3-to-1 in split tests. NEVER
write copy where the brand is the hero.

AIDA, PASTOR, OGILVY'S 10 (supporting frameworks)
  AIDA:   Attention → Interest → Desire → Action
  PASTOR: Problem, Amplify, Story/Solution, Transformation, Offer, Response
  Ogilvy: Headlines matter 5x more than body. Long copy sells if engaging.
          Never write copy you wouldn't want your family to read.
`.trim();

